    "resolution_criteria": "This market will resolve to \"Yes\" if any AI gets a gold medal in the International Math Olympiad by December 31, 2025, 11:59 PM ET. Otherwise this market will resolve to \"No.\"\n\nThe resolution source is the IMO Grand Challenge (https://imo-grand-challenge.github.io/) and the Artificial Intelligence Math Olympiad (AIMO, https://aimoprize.com/). If either source demonstrates that an AI has won the challenge/prize before the resolution date, this market will resolve to \"Yes\".",
    "outcome": "No",
    "explanation": "\n# Required Output Format\n\n## Executive Summary\nDespite significant advancements in artificial intelligence mathematical reasoning throughout 2025, no AI system officially won a gold medal at the 2025 International Mathematical Olympiad (IMO). Leading AI labs, specifically OpenAI and Google DeepMind, successfully developed models capable of achieving \"gold-medal level\" scores by solving 5 out of 6 problems from the 2025 competition. However, these systems were tested in experimental or lab settings and self-graded, rather than participating as official competitors under strict IMO regulations. Consequently, the market correctly resolved to 'No' because achieving a benchmark score contemporaneously is not equivalent to being officially awarded a gold medal by the IMO organizers.\n\n## Timeline Of Key Events\n- **2025-01-15**: Early discussions and round-ups of AI potential at IMO 2025 begin, causing initial market skepticism as the immense difficulty of jumping from 2024's silver-level to gold-level becomes apparent ([art_tech_20250115_012_6cea1933]).\n- **2025-04-08**: Optimism surges as theoretical capabilities of new AI systems are discussed, leading to a temporary shift in prediction markets favoring 'Yes' ([art_tech_20250408_013_e78e9208]).\n- **2025-05-03 & 2025-06-29**: Growing realization that while AI can solve many problems, unguided combinatorial reasoning remains a significant hurdle.\n- **2025-07-19**: The 2025 IMO takes place. AI labs run the newly released problems through their models, solving many of them and prompting immediate claims of \"gold-medal standard\" performance ([art_tech_20250719_019_e12040e4]). The market aggressively flips to 'Yes'.\n- **2025-07-20**: Clarity emerges that OpenAI and DeepMind merely self-graded their AI's solutions outside of official competition. The distinction between a \"gold-medal score\" and an official \"gold medal\" causes the market to rapidly correct back to 'No' ([art_tech_20250720_003_6413e9d1]).\n\n## Causal Chain Analysis\nThe root cause of the intense speculation was the rapid advancement of formal reasoning models by DeepMind and OpenAI, which built upon the silver-medal-level success of 2024. This led to intermediate mechanisms where AI models were trained specifically to tackle IMO-style problems using chain-of-thought and formal provers. The proximate trigger for the massive market volatility in July 2025 was the unauthorized, premature announcement by AI researchers claiming their models had achieved gold-medal performance on the 2025 problems ([art_tech_20250720_003_6413e9d1]). However, this resulted in the final outcome resolving to 'No' because the IMO organizers only award official medals to registered human participants competing under strict, proctored conditions, meaning the AI systems' achievements, while scientifically profound, remained strictly unofficial.\n\n## Countervailing Factors\nThe primary countervailing force was the undeniable technical success of the AI models. Systems like OpenAI's o3 and DeepMind's Gemini 2.5 Pro Deep Think actually did solve enough problems to meet the point threshold for a gold medal (e.g., scoring 5 out of 6 problems). This pushed immense market sentiment toward 'Yes'. However, this force was overwhelmed by the definitional reality of the question: \"winning a gold medal\" at the IMO requires official recognition and participation, which AI systems are categorically ineligible for at this time.\n\n## Event Candidate Inventory\n- E1: Initial assessments of AI capabilities for IMO 2025 are published.\n  - date: 2025-01-15\n  - why it matters causally: Set the baseline expectation for the year, showing the difficulty of the challenge.\n  - source article IDs: art_tech_20250115_012_6cea1933\n- E2: AI labs test their models on the 2025 IMO problems contemporaneously.\n  - date: 2025-07-19\n  - why it matters causally: Generated the actual proofs that met the gold-medal scoring threshold, causing the massive market spike.\n  - source article IDs: art_tech_20250719_019_e12040e4\n- E3: AI researchers prematurely announce \"gold medal\" performance, which is later clarified as unofficial self-grading.\n  - date: 2025-07-20\n  - why it matters causally: Corrected the market misconception, driving the resolution permanently to 'No' as it became clear no official medal was awarded.\n  - source article IDs: art_tech_20250720_003_6413e9d1\n\n## Evidence Mapping Table\n| Claim/Event | Article IDs | Date Support | Confidence (0-1) | Notes |\n| --- | --- | --- | --- | --- |\n| Early 2025 assessments of AI at IMO | art_tech_20250115_012_6cea1933 | 2025-01-15 | 0.9 | Established baseline expectations |\n| AI solves IMO problems at gold standard | art_tech_20250719_019_e12040e4 | 2025-07-19 | 1.0 | Details the specific proofs generated by models |\n| Clarification that results are unofficial | art_tech_20250720_003_6413e9d1 | 2025-07-20 | 1.0 | Explains the self-grading and embargo breach |\n\n## Uncertainties And Alternative Paths\nThe main uncertainty was whether the IMO organizers might create a special official category for AI participants in 2025, or officially award an honorary medal. If the IMO had chosen to formally recognize the AI's submission during the closing ceremonies rather than maintaining its strict human-only official medalist policy, the outcome could have plausibly resolved to 'Yes'. However, the IMO maintained its traditional stance.\n",
